<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900705-0065</DOCNO><DOCID>900705-0065.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Development-Bank Plan   For South Africa Advance</HL><DATE>07/05/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   AFRIC</CO><IN>BANKS (BNK)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- A proposed South African development bank tooka step toward reality when Nelson Mandela met with PeterGoldmark, president of the Rockefeller Foundation.   &quot;What began as a germ of an idea is now a seedling,&quot; Mr.Goldmark said yesterday after his return to New York.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Goldmark had suggested during a New York breakfastwith business leaders for Mr. Mandela June 22 thatcorporations and foundations were interested in a mechanismfor channeling investments to South Africa that could beginto function &quot;the minute a just government is elected.&quot;   Few specifics have been settled, but Mr. Goldmark saidthat after an hour's discussion in Mr. Mandela's London hotelTuesday it was tentatively decided that the developmentbank's objectives for South Africa would be establishment ofan equitable economic structure and investment in roads,irrigation systems and other development infrastructure.   Mr. Goldmark said a &quot;core group&quot; was formed to plan thebank's structure, including himself, African NationalCongress Foreign Secretary Thabo Mbeki, and ANC TreasurerThomas Nkobi. The Rockefeller Foundation &quot;is only to be ofprofessional and technical assistance,&quot; with centralleadership coming from the South African participants, hesaid.</TEXT></DOC>